[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:t-sne-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Methods are commonly divided into linear and nonlinear approaches.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Linear approaches can be further divided into feature selection and feature extraction.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Dimensionality reduction can be used for noise reduction, data visualization, cluster analysis, or as an intermediate step to facilitate other analyses.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The process of feature selection aims to find a suitable subset of the input variables (*features*, or *attributes*) for the task at hand.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The three strategies are: the *filter* strategy (e.g., information gain), the *wrapper* strategy (e.g., accuracy-guided search), and the *embedded* strategy (features are added or removed while building the model based on prediction errors).
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Data analysis such as regression or classification can be done in the reduced space more accurately than in the original space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Feature projection (also called feature extraction) transforms the data from the high-dimensional space to a space of fewer dimensions.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The data transformation may be linear, as in principal component analysis (PCA), but many nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques also exist.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] For multidimensional data, tensor representation can be used in dimensionality reduction through multilinear subspace learning.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The main linear technique for dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis, performs a linear mapping of the data to a lower-dimensional space in such a way that the variance of the data in the low-dimensional representation is maximized.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] In practice, the covariance (and sometimes the correlation) matrix of the data is constructed and the eigenvectors on this matrix are computed.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The eigenvectors that correspond to the largest eigenvalues (the principal components) can now be used to reconstruct a large fraction of the variance of the original data.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Moreover, the first few eigenvectors can often be interpreted in terms of the large-scale physical behavior of the system, because they often contribute the vast majority of the system's energy, especially in low-dimensional systems.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Still, this must be proved on a case-by-case basis as not all systems exhibit this behavior.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The original space (with dimension of the number of points) has been reduced (with data loss, but hopefully retaining the most important variance) to the space spanned by a few eigenvectors.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] NMF decomposes a non-negative matrix to the product of two non-negative ones, which has been a promising tool in fields where only non-negative signals exist, such as astronomy.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] With a stable component basis during construction, and a linear modeling process, sequential NMF is able to preserve the flux in direct imaging of circumstellar structures in astronomy, as one of the methods of detecting exoplanets, especially for the direct imaging of circumstellar discs.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] In comparison with PCA, NMF does not remove the mean of the matrices, which leads to physical non-negative fluxes; therefore NMF is able to preserve more information than PCA as demonstrated by Ren et al.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Principal component analysis can be employed in a nonlinear way by means of the kernel trick.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is capable of constructing nonlinear mappings that maximize the variance in the data.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is called kernel PCA.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Other prominent nonlinear techniques include manifold learning techniques such as Isomap, locally linear embedding (LLE), Hessian LLE, Laplacian eigenmaps, and methods based on tangent space analysis.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] More recently, techniques have been proposed that, instead of defining a fixed kernel, try to learn the kernel using semidefinite programming.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The most prominent example of such a technique is maximum variance unfolding (MVU).
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The central idea of MVU is to exactly preserve all pairwise distances between nearest neighbors (in the inner product space) while maximizing the distances between points that are not nearest neighbors.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] An alternative approach to neighborhood preservation is through the minimization of a cost function that measures differences between distances in the input and output spaces.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] A different approach to nonlinear dimensionality reduction is through the use of autoencoders, a special kind of feedforward neural networks with a bottleneck hidden layer.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The training of deep encoders is typically performed using a greedy layer-wise pre-training (e.g., using a stack of restricted Boltzmann machines) that is followed by a finetuning stage based on backpropagation.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is a generalization of Fisher's linear discriminant, a method used in statistics, pattern recognition, and machine learning to find a linear combination of features that characterizes or separates two or more classes of objects or events.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] GDA deals with nonlinear discriminant analysis using kernel function operator.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The underlying theory is close to the support-vector machines (SVM) insofar as the GDA method provides a mapping of the input vectors into high-dimensional feature space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Similar to LDA, the objective of GDA is to find a projection for the features into a lower dimensional space by maximizing the ratio of between-class scatter to within-class scatter.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Autoencoders can be used to learn nonlinear dimension reduction functions and codings together with an inverse function from the coding to the original representation.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique useful for the visualization of high-dimensional datasets.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] It is not recommended for use in analysis such as clustering or outlier detection since it does not necessarily preserve densities or distances well.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Visually, it is similar to t-SNE, but it assumes that the data is uniformly distributed on a locally connected Riemannian manifold and that the Riemannian metric is locally constant or approximately locally constant.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] For high-dimensional datasets, dimension reduction is usually performed prior to applying a *k*-nearest neighbors (*k*-NN) algorithm in order to mitigate the curse of dimensionality.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] In machine learning, this process is also called low-dimensional embedding.
[src:t-sne-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] A dimensionality reduction technique that is sometimes used in neuroscience is maximally informative dimensions, which finds a lower-dimensional representation of a dataset such that as much information as possible about the original data is preserved.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] High dimensional data can be hard for machines to work with, requiring significant time and space for analysis.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It also presents a challenge for humans, since it's hard to visualize or understand data in more than three dimensions.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Reducing the dimensionality of a data set, while keeping its essential features relatively intact, can make algorithms more efficient and allow analysts to visualize trends and patterns.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The reduced-dimensional representations of data are often referred to as "intrinsic variables".
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] This description implies that these are the values from which the data was produced.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] For example, consider a dataset that contains images of a letter 'A', which has been scaled and rotated by varying amounts.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Each image can be represented as a vector of 1024 pixel values.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Each row is a sample on a two-dimensional manifold in 1024-dimensional space (a Hamming space).
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The intrinsic dimensionality is two, because two variables (rotation and scale) were varied in order to produce the data.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Information about the shape or look of a letter 'A' is not part of the intrinsic variables because it is the same in every instance.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Nonlinear dimensionality reduction will discard the correlated information (the letter 'A') and recover only the varying information (rotation and scale).
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] By comparison, if principal component analysis, which is a linear dimensionality reduction algorithm, is used to reduce this same dataset into two dimensions, the resulting values are not so well organized.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] This demonstrates that the high-dimensional vectors (each representing a letter 'A') that sample this manifold vary in a non-linear manner.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It should be apparent, therefore, that NLDR has several applications in the field of computer-vision.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] For example, consider a robot that uses a camera to navigate in a closed static environment.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The images obtained by that camera can be considered to be samples on a manifold in high-dimensional space, and the intrinsic variables of that manifold will represent the robot's position and orientation.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Invariant manifolds are of general interest for model order reduction in dynamical systems.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] In particular, if there is an attracting invariant manifold in the phase space, nearby trajectories will converge onto it and stay on it indefinitely, rendering it a candidate for dimensionality reduction of the dynamical system.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] While such manifolds are not guaranteed to exist in general, the theory of spectral submanifolds (SSM) gives conditions for the existence of unique attracting invariant objects in a broad class of dynamical systems.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Active research in NLDR seeks to unfold the observation manifolds associated with dynamical systems to develop modeling techniques.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Some of the more prominent **nonlinear dimensionality reduction** techniques are listed below.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Sammon's mapping is one of the first and most popular NLDR techniques.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The self-organizing map (SOM, also called *Kohonen map*) and its probabilistic variant generative topographic mapping (GTM) use a point representation in the embedded space to form a latent variable model based on a non-linear mapping from the embedded space to the high-dimensional space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] These techniques are related to work on density networks, which also are based around the same probabilistic model.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Perhaps the most widely used algorithm for dimensional reduction is kernel PCA.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It then projects the data onto the first *k* eigenvectors of that matrix.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It then projects the transformed data onto the first *k* eigenvectors of that matrix, just like PCA.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It uses the kernel trick to factor away much of the computation, such that the entire process can be performed without actually computing $\Phi (\mathbf {x} )$ .
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Of course $\Phi$ must be chosen such that it has a known corresponding kernel.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Unfortunately, it is not trivial to find a good kernel for a given problem, so KPCA does not yield good results with some problems when using standard kernels.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] For example, it is known to perform poorly with these kernels on the Swiss roll manifold.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] However, one can view certain other methods that perform well in such settings (e.g., Laplacian Eigenmaps, LLE) as special cases of kernel PCA by constructing a data-dependent kernel matrix.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] KPCA has an internal model, so it can be used to map points onto its embedding that were not available at training time.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Laplacian eigenmaps uses spectral techniques to perform dimensionality reduction.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] This technique relies on the basic assumption that the data lies in a low-dimensional manifold in a high-dimensional space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] This algorithm cannot embed out-of-sample points, but techniques based on Reproducing kernel Hilbert space regularization exist for adding this capability.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Such techniques can be applied to other nonlinear dimensionality reduction algorithms as well.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Traditional techniques like principal component analysis do not consider the intrinsic geometry of the data.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Laplacian eigenmaps builds a graph from neighborhood information of the data set.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Each data point serves as a node on the graph and connectivity between nodes is governed by the proximity of neighboring points (using e.g. the k-nearest neighbor algorithm).
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The graph thus generated can be considered as a discrete approximation of the low-dimensional manifold in the high-dimensional space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Minimization of a cost function based on the graph ensures that points close to each other on the manifold are mapped close to each other in the low-dimensional space, preserving local distances.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The eigenfunctions of the Laplace–Beltrami operator on the manifold serve as the embedding dimensions, since under mild conditions this operator has a countable spectrum that is a basis for square integrable functions on the manifold (compare to Fourier series on the unit circle manifold).
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Attempts to place Laplacian eigenmaps on solid theoretical ground have met with some success, as under certain nonrestrictive assumptions, the graph Laplacian matrix has been shown to converge to the Laplace–Beltrami operator as the number of points goes to infinity.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Isomap is a combination of the Floyd–Warshall algorithm with classic Multidimensional Scaling (MDS).
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Classic MDS takes a matrix of pair-wise distances between all points and computes a position for each point.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Isomap assumes that the pair-wise distances are only known between neighboring points, and uses the Floyd–Warshall algorithm to compute the pair-wise distances between all other points.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] This effectively estimates the full matrix of pair-wise geodesic distances between all of the points.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Isomap then uses classic MDS to compute the reduced-dimensional positions of all the points.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Landmark-Isomap is a variant of this algorithm that uses landmarks to increase speed, at the cost of some accuracy.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] In manifold learning, the input data is assumed to be sampled from a low dimensional manifold that is embedded inside of a higher-dimensional vector space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The main intuition behind MVU is to exploit the local linearity of manifolds and create a mapping that preserves local neighbourhoods at every point of the underlying manifold.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Locally-linear Embedding (LLE) was presented at approximately the same time as Isomap.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It has several advantages over Isomap, including faster optimization when implemented to take advantage of sparse matrix algorithms, and better results with many problems.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] LLE also begins by finding a set of the nearest neighbors of each point.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It then computes a set of weights for each point that best describes the point as a linear combination of its neighbors.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Finally, it uses an eigenvector-based optimization technique to find the low-dimensional embedding of points, such that each point is still described with the same linear combination of its neighbors.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] LLE tends to handle non-uniform sample densities poorly because there is no fixed unit to prevent the weights from drifting as various regions differ in sample densities.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The original data points $X_{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{D}$ , and the goal of LLE is to embed each point $X_{i}$ to some low-dimensional point $Y_{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where $d\ll D$ .
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] In the **first** step, it computes, for each point *X**i*, the best approximation of *X**i* based on barycentric coordinates of its neighbors *X**j*.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The original point is approximately reconstructed by a linear combination, given by the weight matrix *W**ij*, of its neighbors.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The weights *W**ij* refer to the amount of contribution the point *X**j* has while reconstructing the point *X**i*.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] These two constraints ensure that W is unaffected by rotation and translation.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] In the **second** step, a neighborhood preserving map is created based the weights.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Unlike in the previous cost function, the weights Wij are kept fixed and the minimization is done on the points Yi to optimize the coordinates.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] This minimization problem can be solved by solving a sparse *N* X *N* eigenvalue problem (*N* being the number of data points), whose bottom *d* nonzero eigen vectors provide an orthogonal set of coordinates.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The only hyperparameter in the algorithm is what counts as a "neighbor" of a point.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Generally the data points are reconstructed from *K* nearest neighbors, as measured by Euclidean distance.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] In this case, the algorithm has only one integer-valued hyperparameter *K,* which can be chosen by cross validation.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Like LLE, Hessian LLE is also based on sparse matrix techniques.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It tends to yield results of a much higher quality than LLE.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Unfortunately, it has a very costly computational complexity, so it is not well-suited for heavily sampled manifolds.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Modified LLE (MLLE) is another LLE variant which uses multiple weights in each neighborhood to address the local weight matrix conditioning problem which leads to distortions in LLE maps.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Loosely speaking the multiple weights are the local orthogonal projection of the original weights produced by LLE.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The theoretical and empirical implications from the correct application of this algorithm are far-reaching.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] LTSA is based on the intuition that when a manifold is correctly unfolded, all of the tangent hyperplanes to the manifold will become aligned.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It begins by computing the *k*-nearest neighbors of every point.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It computes the tangent space at every point by computing the *d*-first principal components in each local neighborhood.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It then optimizes to find an embedding that aligns the tangent spaces.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Maximum Variance Unfolding, Isomap and Locally Linear Embedding share a common intuition relying on the notion that if a manifold is properly unfolded, then variance over the points is maximized.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Its initial step, like Isomap and Locally Linear Embedding, is finding the *k*-nearest neighbors of every point.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It then seeks to solve the problem of maximizing the distance between all non-neighboring points, constrained such that the distances between neighboring points are preserved.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The primary contribution of this algorithm is a technique for casting this problem as a semidefinite programming problem.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Unfortunately, semidefinite programming solvers have a high computational cost.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Like Locally Linear Embedding, it has no internal model.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] An autoencoder is a feed-forward neural network which is trained to approximate the identity function.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] That is, it is trained to map from a vector of values to the same vector.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] When used for dimensionality reduction purposes, one of the hidden layers in the network is limited to contain only a small number of network units.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Thus, the network must learn to encode the vector into a small number of dimensions and then decode it back into the original space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Thus, the first half of the network is a model which maps from high to low-dimensional space, and the second half maps from low to high-dimensional space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Although the idea of autoencoders is quite old, training of deep autoencoders has only recently become possible through the use of restricted Boltzmann machines and stacked denoising autoencoders.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Related to autoencoders is the NeuroScale algorithm, which uses stress functions inspired by multidimensional scaling and Sammon mappings (see above) to learn a non-linear mapping from the high-dimensional to the embedded space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The mappings in NeuroScale are based on radial basis function networks.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Gaussian process latent variable models (GPLVM) are probabilistic dimensionality reduction methods that use Gaussian Processes (GPs) to find a lower dimensional non-linear embedding of high dimensional data.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] They are an extension of the Probabilistic formulation of PCA.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The model is defined probabilistically and the latent variables are then marginalized and parameters are obtained by maximizing the likelihood.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Like kernel PCA they use a kernel function to form a non linear mapping (in the form of a Gaussian process).
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] However, in the GPLVM the mapping is from the embedded(latent) space to the data space (like density networks and GTM) whereas in kernel PCA it is in the opposite direction.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It was originally proposed for visualization of high dimensional data but has been extended to construct a shared manifold model between two observation spaces.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] GPLVM and its many variants have been proposed specially for human motion modeling, e.g., back constrained GPLVM, GP dynamic model (GPDM), balanced GPDM (B-GPDM) and topologically constrained GPDM.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] To capture the coupling effect of the pose and gait manifolds in the gait analysis, a multi-layer joint gait-pose manifolds was proposed.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Relational perspective map is a multidimensional scaling algorithm.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The algorithm finds a configuration of data points on a manifold by simulating a multi-particle dynamic system on a closed manifold, where data points are mapped to particles and distances (or dissimilarity) between data points represent a repulsive force.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] As the manifold gradually grows in size the multi-particle system cools down gradually and converges to a configuration that reflects the distance information of the data points.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Relational perspective map was inspired by a physical model in which positively charged particles move freely on the surface of a ball.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Guided by the Coulomb force between particles, the minimal energy configuration of the particles will reflect the strength of repulsive forces between the particles.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The Relational perspective map was introduced in.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The algorithm firstly used the flat torus as the image manifold, then it has been extended (in the software VisuMap to use other types of closed manifolds, like the sphere, projective space, and Klein bottle, as image manifolds.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Contagion maps use multiple contagions on a network to map the nodes as a point cloud.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] In the case of the Global cascades model the speed of the spread can be adjusted with the threshold parameter $t\in [0,1]$ .
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] For $t=0$ the contagion map is equivalent to the Isomap algorithm.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Curvilinear component analysis (CCA) looks for the configuration of points in the output space that preserves original distances as much as possible while focusing on small distances in the output space (conversely to Sammon's mapping which focus on small distances in original space).
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It should be noticed that CCA, as an iterative learning algorithm, actually starts with focus on large distances (like the Sammon algorithm), then gradually change focus to small distances.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The small distance information will overwrite the large distance information, if compromises between the two have to be made.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The stress function of CCA is related to a sum of right Bregman divergences.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] CDA trains a self-organizing neural network to fit the manifold and seeks to preserve geodesic distances in its embedding.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It is based on Curvilinear Component Analysis (which extended Sammon's mapping), but uses geodesic distances instead.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Diffeomorphic Dimensionality Reduction or *Diffeomap* learns a smooth diffeomorphic mapping which transports the data onto a lower-dimensional linear subspace.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The methods solves for a smooth time indexed vector field such that flows along the field which start at the data points will end at a lower-dimensional linear subspace, thereby attempting to preserve pairwise differences under both the forward and inverse mapping.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Manifold alignment takes advantage of the assumption that disparate data sets produced by similar generating processes will share a similar underlying manifold representation.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] By learning projections from each original space to the shared manifold, correspondences are recovered and knowledge from one domain can be transferred to another.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Most manifold alignment techniques consider only two data sets, but the concept extends to arbitrarily many initial data sets.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Diffusion maps leverages the relationship between heat diffusion and a random walk (Markov Chain); an analogy is drawn between the diffusion operator on a manifold and a Markov transition matrix operating on functions defined on the graph whose nodes were sampled from the manifold.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] In particular, let a data set be represented by $\mathbf {X} =[x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}]\in \Omega \subset \mathbf {R^{D}}$ .
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The underlying assumption of diffusion map is that the high-dimensional data lies on a low-dimensional manifold of dimension $\mathbf {d}$ .
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Let **X** represent the data set and $\mu$ represent the distribution of the data points on **X**.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Further, define a **kernel** which represents some notion of affinity of the points in **X**.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Thus one can think of the individual data points as the nodes of a graph and the kernel *k* as defining some sort of affinity on that graph.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The graph is symmetric by construction since the kernel is symmetric.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It is easy to see here that from the tuple (**X**,**k**) one can construct a reversible Markov Chain.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] This technique is common to a variety of fields and is known as the graph Laplacian.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] For example, the graph **K** = (*X*,*E*) can be constructed using a Gaussian kernel.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] In the above equation, $x_{i}\sim x_{j}$ denotes that $x_{i}$ is a nearest neighbor of $x_{j}$ .
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Properly, Geodesic distance should be used to actually measure distances on the manifold.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Since the exact structure of the manifold is not available, for the nearest neighbors the geodesic distance is approximated by euclidean distance.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The former means that very little diffusion has taken place while the latter implies that the diffusion process is nearly complete.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Different strategies to choose $\sigma$ can be found in.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] P now represents a Markov chain. $P(x_{i},x_{j})$ is the probability of transitioning from $x_{i}$ to $x_{j}$ in one time step.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Similarly the probability of transitioning from $x_{i}$ to $x_{j}$ in **t** time steps is given by $P^{t}(x_{i},x_{j})$ .
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Here $P^{t}$ is the matrix P multiplied by itself **t** times.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The Markov matrix P constitutes some notion of local geometry of the data set **X**.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The major difference between diffusion maps and principal component analysis is that only local features of the data are considered in diffusion maps as opposed to taking correlations of the entire data set.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] K defines a random walk on the data set which means that the kernel captures some local geometry of data set.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The Markov chain defines fast and slow directions of propagation through the kernel values.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] As the walk propagates forward in time, the local geometry information aggregates in the same way as local transitions (defined by differential equations) of the dynamical system.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] For fixed t, $D_{t}$ defines a distance between any two points of the data set based on path connectivity: the value of $D_{t}(x,y)$ will be smaller the more paths that connect **x** to **y** and vice versa.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Local Multidimensional Scaling performs multidimensional scaling in local regions, and then uses convex optimization to fit all the pieces together.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Nonlinear PCA (NLPCA) uses backpropagation to train a multi-layer perceptron (MLP) to fit to a manifold.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Unlike typical MLP training, which only updates the weights, NLPCA updates both the weights and the inputs.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] That is, both the weights and inputs are treated as latent values.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] After training, the latent inputs are a low-dimensional representation of the observed vectors, and the MLP maps from that low-dimensional representation to the high-dimensional observation space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Manifold Sculpting uses graduated optimization to find an embedding.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Like other algorithms, it computes the *k*-nearest neighbors and tries to seek an embedding that preserves relationships in local neighborhoods.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It slowly scales variance out of higher dimensions, while simultaneously adjusting points in lower dimensions to preserve those relationships.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] If the rate of scaling is small, it can find very precise embeddings.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It boasts higher empirical accuracy than other algorithms with several problems.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It can also be used to refine the results from other manifold learning algorithms.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It struggles to unfold some manifolds, however, unless a very slow scaling rate is used.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] RankVisu is designed to preserve rank of neighborhood rather than distance.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] RankVisu is especially useful on difficult tasks (when the preservation of distance cannot be achieved satisfyingly).
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Indeed, the rank of neighborhood is less informative than distance (ranks can be deduced from distances but distances cannot be deduced from ranks) and its preservation is thus easier.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Topologically constrained isometric embedding (TCIE) is an algorithm based on approximating geodesic distances after filtering geodesics inconsistent with the Euclidean metric.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] Aimed at correcting the distortions caused when Isomap is used to map intrinsically non-convex data, TCIE uses weight least-squares MDS in order to obtain a more accurate mapping.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The TCIE algorithm first detects possible boundary points in the data, and during computation of the geodesic length marks inconsistent geodesics, to be given a small weight in the weighted stress majorization that follows.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding (t-SNE) is widely used.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It is one of a family of stochastic neighbor embedding methods.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The algorithm computes the probability that pairs of datapoints in the high-dimensional space are related, and then chooses low-dimensional embeddings which produce a similar distribution.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] It works in a similar fashion as the t-SNE, with the main difference being the inclusion of a repulsive term to move far points away from each other.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] A method based on proximity matrices is one where the data is presented to the algorithm in the form of a similarity matrix or a distance matrix.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] These methods all fall under the broader class of metric multidimensional scaling.
[src:t-sne-embedding/manifold-learning] The variations tend to be differences in how the proximity data is computed; for example, isomap, locally linear embeddings, maximum variance unfolding, and Sammon mapping (which is not in fact a mapping) are examples of metric multidimensional scaling methods.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] In information theory, **perplexity** is a measure of uncertainty for a discrete probability distribution.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] The perplexity of a fair coin toss is 2, and that of a fair die roll is 6; and generally, for a probability distribution with exactly N outcomes each having a probability of exactly 1 / *N*, the perplexity is simply N.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] But perplexity can also be applied to unfair dice, and to other non-uniform probability distributions.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] It can be defined as the exponentiation of the information entropy.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] The larger the perplexity, the less likely it is that an observer can guess the value which will be drawn from the distribution.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Perplexity was originally introduced in 1977 in the context of speech recognition by Frederick Jelinek, Robert Leroy Mercer, Lalit R.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] The perplexity PP of a discrete probability distribution p is a concept widely used in information theory, machine learning, and statistical modeling.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] It is defined as $\mathrm {PP} (p)=\prod _{x}p(x)^{-p(x)}=b^{-\sum _{x}p(x)\log _{b}p(x)},$ where x ranges over the events, where 0−0 is defined to be 1, and where the value of b does not affect the result; b can be chosen to be 2, 10, e, or any other positive value other than 1.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] In some contexts, this measure is also referred to as the *(order-1 true) diversity*.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] The logarithm log PP(*p*) is the entropy of the distribution; it is given the unit shannon (bit) if the base of the logarithm is 2, and nat if the natural logarithm is used.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Perplexity of a random variable X may be defined as the perplexity of the distribution over its possible values x.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] It can be thought of as a measure of uncertainty or "surprise" related to the outcomes.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] For a probability distribution p where exactly k outcomes each have a probability of 1 / *k* and all other outcomes have a probability of zero, the perplexity of this distribution is simply k.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] This is because the distribution models a fair k-sided die, with each of the k outcomes being equally likely.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] In this context, the perplexity k indicates that there is as much uncertainty as there would be when rolling a fair k-sided die.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Even if a random variable has more than k possible outcomes, the perplexity will still be k if the distribution is uniform over k outcomes and zero for the rest.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Thus, a random variable with a perplexity of k can be described as being "k-ways perplexed", meaning it has the same level of uncertainty as a fair k-sided die.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Perplexity is sometimes used as a measure of the difficulty of a prediction problem.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] It is, however, generally not a straightforward representation of the relevant probability.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] For example, if you have two choices, one with probability 0.9, your probability of a correct guess using the optimal strategy is 0.9.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] The inverse of the perplexity, 1/1.38 = 0.72, is not equal to the probability 0.9.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] The perplexity is the exponentiation of the entropy, a more commonly encountered quantity.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Entropy measures the expected or "average" number of bits required to encode the outcome of the random variable using an optimal variable-length code.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] It can also be regarded as the expected information gain from learning the outcome of the random variable, providing insight into the uncertainty and complexity of the underlying probability distribution.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] A model of an unknown probability distribution p may be proposed based on a training sample that was drawn from p.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Given a proposed probability model q, one may evaluate q by asking how well it predicts a separate test sample *x*1, *x*2, ..., *x**N* also drawn from p.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Better models q of the unknown distribution p will tend to assign higher probabilities *q*(*x**i*) to the test events.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Thus, they have lower perplexity because they are less surprised by the test sample.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] This is equivalent to saying that better models have higher likelihoods for the test data, which leads to a lower perplexity value.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] The exponent, ${\textstyle -{\frac {1}{N}}\sum _{i=1}^{N}\log _{b}q(x_{i})}$ , with *b* = 2, may be regarded as the average number of bits needed to represent a test event *x**i* if one uses an optimal code based on q.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Low-perplexity models do a better job of compressing the test sample, requiring few bits per test element on average because *q*(*x**i*) tends to be high.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] The exponent may also be interpreted as a cross-entropy: $H({\tilde {p}},q)=-\sum _{x}{\tilde {p}}(x)\log _{b}q(x),$ where ~*p* denotes the empirical distribution of the test sample (i.e., ~*p*(*x*) = *n*/*N* if x appeared n times in the test sample of size N).
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] By the definition of KL divergence, it is also equal to *H*(~*p*) + *D*KL(~*p* || *q*), which is ≥ *H*(~*p*).
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Consequently, the perplexity is minimized when *q* = ~*p*.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] In natural language processing (NLP), a corpus is a structured collection of texts or documents, and a language model is a probability distribution over entire texts or documents.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] This normalizes the perplexity by the length of the text, allowing for more meaningful comparisons between different texts or models rather than documents.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Suppose the average text *x**i* in the corpus has a probability of 2−190 according to the language model.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] This would give a model perplexity of 2190 for a sentence.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] However, in NLP, it is more common to normalize by the length of a text.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Thus, if the test sample has a length of 1000 tokens, and could be coded using 7.95 bits per token, one could report a model perplexity of token of 27.95 = 247.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] In other words, the model is as confused on test data as if it had to choose uniformly and independently among 247 possibilities for each token.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] There are two standard evaluation metrics for language models: perplexity or word error rate (WER).
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] The second metric, perplexity (of a token), is an information theoretic measure that evaluates the similarity of proposed model m to the original distribution p.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] It can be computed as a inverse of (geometric) average probability of test set T $\mathrm {PPL} (D)={\sqrt[{N}]{\frac {1}{m(T)}}}=2^{-{\frac {1}{N}}\log _{2}\left(m(T)\right)},$ where N is the number of tokens in test set T.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Since 2007, significant advancements in language modeling have emerged, particularly with the advent of deep learning techniques.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Token-normalized perplexity, a measure that quantifies the predictive power of a language model, has remained central to evaluating models such as the dominant transformer models like Google's BERT, OpenAI's GPT-4 and other large language models (LLMs).
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] This measure was employed to compare different models on the same dataset and guide the optimization of hyperparameters, although it has been found sensitive to factors such as linguistic features and sentence length.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] Despite its pivotal role in language model development, perplexity has shown limitations, particularly as an inadequate predictor of speech recognition performance, overfitting and generalization, raising questions about the benefits of blindly optimizing perplexity alone.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] The lowest perplexity that had been published on the Brown Corpus (1 million words of American English of varying topics and genres) as of 1992 is indeed about 247 per word/token, corresponding to a cross-entropy of log2 247 = 7.95 bits per word or 1.75 bits per letter using a trigram model.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] While this figure represented the state of the art (SOTA) at the time, advancements in techniques such as deep learning have led to significant improvements in perplexity on other benchmarks, such as the One Billion Word Benchmark.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] In the context of the Brown Corpus, simply guessing that the next word is "the" will achieve an accuracy of 7%, contrasting with the 1/247 = 0.4% that might be expected from a naive use of perplexity.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] This difference underscores the importance of the statistical model used and the nuanced nature of perplexity as a measure of predictiveness.
[src:t-sne-embedding/perplexity] The guess is based on unigram statistics, not on the trigram statistics that yielded the perplexity of 247, and utilizing trigram statistics would further refine the prediction.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] The t-SNE algorithm comprises two main stages.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] First, t-SNE constructs a probability distribution over pairs of high-dimensional objects in such a way that similar objects are assigned a higher probability while dissimilar points are assigned a lower probability.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] Second, t-SNE defines a similar probability distribution over the points in the low-dimensional map, and it minimizes the Kullback–Leibler divergence (KL divergence) between the two distributions with respect to the locations of the points in the map.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] While the original algorithm uses the Euclidean distance between objects as the base of its similarity metric, this can be changed as appropriate.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] t-SNE has been used for visualization in a wide range of applications, including genomics, computer security research, natural language processing, music analysis, cancer research, bioinformatics, geological domain interpretation, and biomedical signal processing.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] For a data set with n elements, t-SNE runs in $O(n^{2})$ time and requires $O(n^{2})$ space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] Given a set of N high-dimensional objects $\mathbf {x} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {x} _{N}$ , t-SNE first computes probabilities $p_{ij}$ that are proportional to the similarity of objects $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ and $\mathbf {x} _{j}$ , as follows.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] Note the above denominator ensures $\sum _{j}p_{j\mid i}=1$ for all i .
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] This is motivated because $p_{i}$ and $p_{j}$ from the N samples are estimated as 1/N, so the conditional probability can be written as $p_{i\mid j}=Np_{ij}$ and $p_{j\mid i}=Np_{ji}$ .
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] Since $p_{ij}=p_{ji}$ , you can obtain previous formula.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] The bandwidth of the Gaussian kernels $\sigma _{i}$ is set in such a way that the entropy of the conditional distribution equals a predefined entropy using the bisection method.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] As a result, the bandwidth is adapted to the density of the data: smaller values of $\sigma _{i}$ are used in denser parts of the data space.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] The perplexity is a hand-chosen parameter of t-SNE, and as the authors state, "perplexity can be interpreted as a smooth measure of the effective number of neighbors.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] The performance of SNE is fairly robust to changes in the perplexity, and typical values are between 5 and 50.".
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] Since the Gaussian kernel uses the Euclidean distance $\lVert x_{i}-x_{j}\rVert$ , it is affected by the curse of dimensionality, and in high dimensional data when distances lose the ability to discriminate, the $p_{ij}$ become too similar (asymptotically, they would converge to a constant).
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] It has been proposed to adjust the distances with a power transform, based on the intrinsic dimension of each point, to alleviate this.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] t-SNE aims to learn a d -dimensional map $\mathbf {y} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {y} _{N}$ (with $\mathbf {y} _{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ and d typically chosen as 2 or 3) that reflects the similarities $p_{ij}$ as well as possible.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] To this end, it measures similarities $q_{ij}$ between two points in the map $\mathbf {y} _{i}$ and $\mathbf {y} _{j}$ , using a very similar approach.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] Herein a heavy-tailed Student t-distribution (with one-degree of freedom, which is the same as a Cauchy distribution) is used to measure similarities between low-dimensional points in order to allow dissimilar objects to be modeled far apart in the map.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] The minimization of the Kullback–Leibler divergence with respect to the points $\mathbf {y} _{i}$ is performed using gradient descent.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] The result of this optimization is a map that reflects the similarities between the high-dimensional inputs.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] While t-SNE plots often seem to display clusters, the visual clusters can be strongly influenced by the chosen parameterization (especially the perplexity) and so a good understanding of the parameters for t-SNE is needed.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] Such "clusters" can be shown to even appear in structured data with no clear clustering, and so may be false findings.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] Similarly, the size of clusters produced by t-SNE is not informative, and neither is the distance between clusters.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] Thus, interactive exploration may be needed to choose parameters and validate results.
[src:t-sne-embedding/t-distributed-stochastic-neighbor-embedding] It has been shown that t-SNE can often recover well-separated clusters, and with special parameter choices, approximates a simple form of spectral clustering.
